In [[mathematics]], '''Kronecker's congruence''', introduced by [[Leopold Kronecker|Kronecker]], states that :<math> \Phi_p(x,y)\equiv (x-y^p)(x^p-y)\bmod p,</math> where ''p'' is a prime and Φ<sub>''p''</sub>(''x'',''y'') is the modular polynomial of order ''p'', given by :<math>\Phi_n(x,j) = \prod_\tau (x-j(\tau))</math> for ''j'' the [[elliptic modular function]] and τ running through classes of imaginary quadratic integers of discriminant&nbsp;''n''.
